= El apellido

Michoacán swears in a new governor this season, and the Republic performs its ritual arithmetic on the name: Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas Solórzano, forty-six, engineer — the son. The son of the only president the Mexican poor ever canonized, the man who gave the land and took the oil, whose portrait hangs in ejido offices next to the Virgin and ahead of the current president, whichever president is current.

The son is PRI, of course; there is no other door to a governorship. He rose the system's way — the Senate, the forestry undersecretariat, the Balsas trust his father ran before him — and the system, watching him, has never been sure what it raised: a loyal engineer with a valuable surname, or a long instrument of his father's unfinished business, waiting with the patience the father was famous for.

Your Michoacán committees report the inauguration's oddities: campesino delegations received before businessmen; an inaugural address that quoted the Constitution's Article 27 — the land — from memory, at length, in a tone nobody mistook for ceremony.

- @observar: Watch him. A note in the file: the surname is not yet a politics, but it is not nothing.
- @tantear: Send a quiet feeler through the agrarista old guard — men who rode with the father and know how to visit a son.

@observar
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: political_capital += 1

The file opens with a single page. It will thicken on its own schedule, not yours — but when the system finally forces the son to choose between the surname and the party, you will at least not be surprised. Most of the Republic will be.

@tantear
go-to: post_event
choose-if: sup_peasants >= 12 or ax_nacpop >= 5
unavailable-subtitle: You have no agrarista old guard to send — the campo barely knows you, and the national-popular register is not one your party speaks.
on-arrival: cd_rel += 1; ax_nacpop += 2; expediente += 2; fac_ortodoxos -= 2

An old man who received his ejido's papers from the father's own hand in 1936 travels to Morelia with a letter that says almost nothing and means a great deal. He is received — that is the entire event, and in the grammar of the system it is a paragraph. The governor asks after the harvest, after the prisoners of the old strikes, after nothing political whatsoever; and at the door, in parting, says only: *hay tiempo.* There is time. The ortodoxos, hearing of it, want it minuted that socialists do not court PRI governors. It is so minuted. The letter is not withdrawn.

