= El gobernador que recibe

The delegation is the campo's usual arithmetic of grievance — an ejido's water stolen upstream by a cacique's pumps, three leaders jailed on invented rustling charges, the agrarian office's antechamber where petitions age into archaeology. What is unusual is the outcome: in Michoacán, the governor receives them.

Receives them, hears the water case to the end, sends an engineer — himself an engineer, he notes — to look at the pumps, and has the rustling charges reviewed by a judge who suddenly remembers the law. It is nothing: one valley, one cacique inconvenienced, three men home for the planting. It is also, in the sexenio of austerity by spreadsheet, when the capital's answer to the campo is a lecture on efficiency, the only place in the Republic where the state behaved this month the way the murals promise.

Your Michoacán cadres, who organized the delegation, take note of both facts: that it worked, and that it worked because of who his father was — and who he is deciding, visibly, slowly, to become.

- @archivar: File it. The son is building something with the surname; when it needs allies, it will know where organized campesinos are found.

@archivar
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: cd_rel += 1; sup_peasants += 2; political_capital += 1

In the file that will matter in 1987, another page: *recibe; resuelve; recuerda.* He receives; he resolves; he remembers. The Corriente, when it forms, will not form in a vacuum — and the flood, when it comes, will already know its own tributaries.

