= La guerra de las actas

Between the night the screens died and the September session that must "qualify" the election, the Republic lives inside an argument about paper: the ballot packets, sealed and stacked in the Legislative Palace's basements under military guard, which the opposition demands be opened and the regime has resolved to keep closed at any grammatical cost. Whoever controls the paper controls the story; whoever controls the story controls what the soldiers think they are guarding.

The FDN's strategy runs through the plazas — half a million in the Zócalo, disciplined and terrible. Yours can run deeper, because your people counted the vote at the tables.

- @publicar_paralelo: Publish the parallel count — district by district, acta by acta, a book the size of a phone directory, sold at cost on every corner.
- @cerco_testigos: The witness cordon: every casilla official who signed an acta contacted, affirmed, notarized — a standing army of signatures the regime cannot burn.
- @guardar_polvora: Keep the powder dry: preserve the archive, protect the people, spend nothing on a fight the Chamber has already scripted.

@publicar_paralelo
go-to: post_event
choose-if: red_casillas >= 30 and funds >= 4
unavailable-subtitle: A parallel count worth printing requires a network that actually counted (30 casillas) and paper money.
on-arrival: funds -= 4; alquimia_expuesta = 1; fe_voto += 4; legitimidad_regimen -= 4; political_capital += 3; expediente += 3

The book has no adjectives — that is its violence. Columns of numbers, photographed actas, the arithmetic performed in public at a table outside the Palacio de Minería by accountants who volunteer in relays. The regime's spokesmen call it partial, which is true: it covers only where witnesses stood. That sentence, examined, concedes everything. The book sells out four printings, and in the vocabulary of the Republic the phrase *se cayó el sistema* completes its migration from excuse to verdict.

@cerco_testigos
go-to: post_event
choose-if: red_casillas >= 20
unavailable-subtitle: The cordon is built from your casilla people — and you did not field enough of them.
on-arrival: red_casillas += 6; fe_voto += 2; unity += 2; expediente += 2

Through August the network does the unglamorous thing one more time: finds every citizen who signed a table's acta, sits in their kitchen, asks them to affirm before a notary what they counted. Thousands say yes — schoolteachers, shopkeepers, a police sergeant's wife — because the asking is done by neighbors, not parties. The packets can burn now; the count has been moved somewhere fire does not reach: onto the Republic's kitchen tables, into its stubborn civic memory. The next reform will be drafted by men who know exactly how many notarized signatures are waiting to be subpoenaed.

@guardar_polvora
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: funds += 2; unity -= 2; fe_voto -= 1

The archive is tripled and buried; the couriers stand down; the plazas fill and empty without your maximum effort. It is defensible — the Chamber's script was indeed already written — and the defense will be made, at length, in meetings for years. What is not recoverable is the moment: there are seasons when a movement banks its strength, and seasons when strength unspent simply expires. Which this was, the veterans will argue past midnight for a decade.
